# Code Quality Standards

## Development Tools

- Use pre-commit hooks for automated code quality checks
- Configure Ruff for fast Python linting
- Use Black for consistent code formatting
- Use prettier for JSON, YAML, and Markdown formatting
- Run django-upgrade to maintain modern Django patterns
- Use mypy for static type checking

## Pre-commit Configuration

- Run all checks before commits
- Exclude migration files and docs from most checks
- Use consistent Python version (3.11) across tools
- Include security checks (detect-private-key)
- Format configuration files (JSON, YAML, TOML)
- Check for common issues (trailing whitespace, large files)

## Code Formatting

- Use Black with 88-character line length
- Use double quotes for strings consistently
- Group imports: standard library, third-party, local
- Sort imports alphabetically within groups
- Use trailing commas in multi-line structures
- Format docstrings consistently

## Linting Standards

- Fix all Ruff errors and warnings
- Use type hints for all function signatures
- Follow PEP 8 naming conventions
- Avoid unused imports and variables
- Use f-strings for string formatting
- Prefer pathlib over os.path for file operations

## Documentation Standards

- Write docstrings for all public classes and functions
- Use Google or NumPy docstring format
- Include type information in docstrings
- Document complex algorithms and business logic
- Keep README and documentation up to date
- Use meaningful variable and function names

## Performance Standards

- Profile code before optimizing
- Use appropriate data structures
- Avoid premature optimization
- Cache expensive computations when appropriate
- Use database query optimization
- Monitor memory usage for large datasets

## Security Standards

- Validate all user inputs
- Use parameterized queries to prevent SQL injection
- Store secrets in environment variables
- Use HTTPS for all external communications
- Implement proper authentication and authorization
- Log security-relevant events

## Makefile Targets

- Provide consistent development commands
- Use virtual environments (uv venv)
- Include database management commands
- Provide testing and coverage commands
- Include deployment and build commands
- Document all available targets

## Example

<example>
# Good pyproject.toml configuration
[tool.ruff]
target-version = "py38"
line-length = 88
select = [
    "E",  # pycodestyle errors
    "W",  # pycodestyle warnings
    "F",  # pyflakes
    "I",  # isort
    "B",  # flake8-bugbear
    "C4", # flake8-comprehensions
    "UP", # pyupgrade
]
ignore = [
    "E501",  # line too long (handled by black)
    "B008",  # do not perform function calls in argument defaults
]

[tool.ruff.per-file-ignores]
"__init__.py" = ["F401"]  # Allow unused imports in __init__.py
"tests/**/*.py" = ["B011"]  # Allow assert False in tests

[tool.black]
line-length = 88
target-version = ['py38', 'py39', 'py310', 'py311']
include = '\.pyi?$'
extend-exclude = '''
/(
  migrations/
  | venv/
  | .venv/
)/
'''

[tool.coverage.run]
source = "src"
omit = [
    "*/migrations/*",
    "*/tests/*",
    "*/venv/*",
    "manage.py",
]

[tool.coverage.report]
exclude_lines = [
    "pragma: no cover",
    "def __repr__",
    "raise AssertionError",
    "raise NotImplementedError",
]
</example>

<example type="invalid">
# Avoid - inconsistent configuration, missing tools
[tool.ruff]
# No target version specified
line-length = 120  # Different from Black
